[11:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than Nvidia\'s state-of-the-art chips. And get&nbsp; this, not only is it faster, but it also costs 20&nbsp;&nbsp; times less to build and it consumes 10 times less&nbsp; power. So, how exactly does this work? You see,&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an AI model is basically a neural network. This&nbsp; is currently made of code and this code lives in&nbsp;&nbsp; software. For example, a transformer could live in&nbsp; this PyTorch code. Now, this software needs to be&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'powered by hardware in order to run. But because&nbsp; of this disconnect between software and hardware,&nbsp;&nbsp; it\'s not as efficient. But here, what Talis has&nbsp; done is they\'ve basically hardcoded the AI model,&nbsp;&nbsp; specifically Llama 3.1, onto the chip itself.&nbsp; So this AI model that lives inside this chip can&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[11:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now respond to you in real time as fast as the&nbsp; speed of thought. You don\'t even need to wait&nbsp;&nbsp; for the sentence to complete. And I think this&nbsp; would be the future of AI models. We need custom&nbsp;&nbsp; hardware that\'s designed specifically for these AI&nbsp; models so that they can be hard-coded into these&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chips. This design merges memory and computation&nbsp; together all on just one chip which unifies the&nbsp;&nbsp; entire system. You don\'t need any big cooling&nbsp; or complicated components. And this helps cut&nbsp;&nbsp;'

[12:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down the costs significantly and also make it way&nbsp; faster. But here\'s the main problem I have with&nbsp;&nbsp; this. So this chip is built specifically for Llama&nbsp; 3.1. It\'s not going to work if you add DeepSeek&nbsp;&nbsp; or Quen or another AI model onto this. So at least&nbsp; currently the technology is that you need to build&nbsp;&nbsp;'

